05:51.985 --> 05:53.318
(train whistle toots)

05:53.320 --> 06:00.225
(soft dramatic music)

06:00.360 --> 06:03.795
♪

06:03.831 --> 06:09.801
(indistinct chatter)

06:09.837 --> 06:16.842
(soft jazz music)

06:16.844 --> 06:18.243
♪

06:18.378 --> 06:21.012
Get this stock tip to
anderson in car 6.

06:21.014 --> 06:28.286
(soft jazz music)

06:28.355 --> 06:30.088
Male passenger:
<i> Some of them are</i>
<i> spotted like a leopard,</i>

06:30.223 --> 06:31.089
<i> Pink and black.</i>

06:31.224 --> 06:32.591
Boy passenger:
<i> Oh.</i>

06:34.862 --> 06:36.327
Thank you kindly, sir.

06:37.364 --> 06:38.429
Junior:
<i> Listen to me,</i>

06:38.465 --> 06:40.298
<i> You take that test</i>
<i> and don't you fail.</i>

06:44.037 --> 06:50.174
(dramatic music swells)

06:50.210 --> 06:52.677
(train whistle blows)

06:52.713 --> 06:55.513
(train roaring)

07:00.654 --> 07:01.787
Mr. Helm,
any improvement?

07:01.922 --> 07:03.121
Helm:
<i> Enter.</i>

07:04.391 --> 07:06.658
(helm grunts)

07:08.762 --> 07:11.195
My colon is still
trying to tear its way out.

07:11.899 --> 07:13.131
You know, I (stammers)...

07:13.266 --> 07:15.667
I know oysters don't
agree with me,

07:15.736 --> 07:18.336
But damned if I can't
stop eating them.

07:19.640 --> 07:22.073
Well next time I'll draw the
line at three orders, sir.

07:22.075 --> 07:23.408
In the meantime,

07:23.410 --> 07:25.143
<i> I have something</i>
<i> that should help.</i>

07:25.746 --> 07:27.044
Bacon fat.

07:27.080 --> 07:28.346
Old trench remedy.

07:28.415 --> 07:30.348
<i> Soldiers used to use the</i>
<i> grease from the tins.</i>

07:30.417 --> 07:31.716
You served?

07:32.586 --> 07:33.818
Yes sir.

07:33.887 --> 07:37.823
Well I know they made light
of you second battalion boys,

07:37.958 --> 07:39.891
<i> But we can hardly</i>
<i> fight a war</i>

07:39.927 --> 07:41.893
<i> Without somebody</i>
<i> clearing a path.</i>

07:42.930 --> 07:44.395
I couldn't agree more sir.

07:45.065 --> 07:46.731
However, I was infantry.

07:48.735 --> 07:49.901
Huh.

07:49.970 --> 07:51.903
Junior:
<i> I hope this should clear</i>
<i> out the fire in no time.</i>

07:51.939 --> 07:54.706
(helm grunts)

07:57.277 --> 08:08.052
(helm grunts)
(suspenseful music)

08:08.121 --> 08:12.590
(train whistle blows)
(suspenseful dramatic music)

08:12.726 --> 08:14.425
Us customs supervisor:
<i> Have your passports ready!</i>

08:18.131 --> 08:19.865
<i> Have your passports ready.</i>

08:20.000 --> 08:24.602
(suspenseful music)

08:24.738 --> 08:26.070
Us customs.

08:26.139 --> 08:31.609
(suspenseful music)

08:31.645 --> 08:32.944
(knocks on door)

08:32.980 --> 08:37.615
(suspenseful music)

08:37.651 --> 08:39.951
Junior:
<i> Ah, that luggage belongs</i>
<i> to general consul helm.</i>

08:39.987 --> 08:43.655
(suspenseful music)

08:43.657 --> 08:44.990
Customs officer:
<i> Us customs.</i>

08:44.992 --> 08:49.160
(suspenseful music)

08:49.162 --> 08:50.495
(helm grunts)

08:50.630 --> 08:52.163
Junior:
<i> He's unwell right now but</i>
<i> I'll be sure to tell him</i>

08:52.165 --> 08:53.565
<i> You rifled through</i>
<i> his things.</i>

08:53.700 --> 08:55.433
Perhaps you'd like
to tell him yourself?

08:55.568 --> 09:01.740
(helm grunts)
(suspenseful music)

09:01.875 --> 09:08.947
(suspenseful music)

09:09.016 --> 09:12.650
(upbeat blues music)

09:12.686 --> 09:15.787
(train whistle blows)

09:15.856 --> 09:22.861
(upbeat blues music)

09:22.863 --> 09:24.596
♪

09:24.731 --> 09:26.464
(train brakes squeal)

09:27.568 --> 09:29.500
Yes ma'am, I'm gonna
get these in your car.

09:31.038 --> 09:32.503
This way, ma'am.

09:34.207 --> 09:35.607
Right this way.

09:36.743 --> 09:38.142
This gentlemen will
get these in your car.

09:38.211 --> 09:39.477
Female passenger:
<i> Porter, your tip!</i>

09:39.546 --> 09:46.484
(suspenseful dramatic music)

09:46.553 --> 09:48.486
♪

09:48.555 --> 09:51.489
Bobby:
<i> I gotta vet it junior,</i>
<i> you know that.</i>

09:52.893 --> 09:57.528
For waterin' down or switched
labels or any other thing.

09:57.564 --> 09:58.496
You might not stoop to it,

09:58.565 --> 10:00.832
But the fella that sold
it to you coulda.

10:02.402 --> 10:04.803
<i> What if I told you I had a</i>
<i> buyer lookin' for an increase</i>

10:04.938 --> 10:06.537
On your regular inventory?

10:07.941 --> 10:09.707
What kinda increase?

10:09.843 --> 10:10.909
Fifty bottles.

10:11.044 --> 10:12.543
This buyer's your regular?

10:13.080 --> 10:14.479
Not exactly, no.

10:17.283 --> 10:18.683
So he's your friend?

10:20.787 --> 10:22.320
Well, I-I wouldn't say that.

10:22.455 --> 10:23.721
But you vouch for him.

10:24.958 --> 10:26.591
You'd trust him with your
life if it came down to it.

10:26.593 --> 10:28.893
That's why you asked me
to trust you with mine?

10:31.765 --> 10:33.031
Six bottles.

10:38.105 --> 10:40.672
Don't you want a better life
for your boy than you got?

10:40.807 --> 10:42.406
Bobby if you ever talk
about my son again,

10:42.442 --> 10:44.208
I'll rip your heart out
where you fucking stand!

10:47.614 --> 10:49.080
What the fuck is
wrong you with you?!

10:49.116 --> 10:50.414
Just think on it jun!

10:51.785 --> 10:53.051
Fifty bottles a run?

10:54.621 --> 10:56.021
Grown-up money!

11:00.160 --> 11:02.426
Rose:
<i> I don't know how he got</i>
<i> that piece of glass.</i>

11:03.630 --> 11:04.963
I-I try to keep
my eyes on him

11:04.965 --> 11:07.298
But he's quicker
than people think.

11:07.300 --> 11:08.933
Marlene:
<i> No one is blaming</i>
<i> you, rose.</i>

11:11.304 --> 11:12.737
<i> This might sting a little.</i>

11:18.311 --> 11:20.244
Ten drops with water,
twice a day.

11:21.681 --> 11:23.915
<i> And I'll be back next</i>
<i> week to check on isaac.</i>

11:25.819 --> 11:27.218
He-he won't be here.

11:28.321 --> 11:30.922
<i> They got a spot for</i>
<i> him in kingston.</i>

11:30.991 --> 11:32.256
The asylum?

11:33.026 --> 11:34.258
Rose:
<i> Boys like ours,</i>

11:34.327 --> 11:38.663
They need more help than
we know how to give.

11:38.798 --> 11:39.897
Marlene:
<i> No.</i>

11:39.899 --> 11:41.733
<i> They just see life</i>
<i> through different windows.</i>

11:50.510 --> 11:52.343
I know you mean
well marlene

11:52.345 --> 11:54.345
But we could collect more if
we didn't spend extra time

11:54.347 --> 11:55.446
At each house.

11:55.515 --> 11:56.981
They don't have anyone
else to help them.

11:57.017 --> 11:59.184
Gwen:
<i> Well, you try</i>
<i> explaining that to eli</i>

11:59.186 --> 12:00.484
When we get to the office.

12:01.554 --> 12:08.492
(dramatic music)

12:08.528 --> 12:19.370
♪

12:19.372 --> 12:22.640
I don't expect we can compete
with the likes of new york.

12:22.709 --> 12:26.978
The unia is about improving the
lives of negroes everywhere.

12:27.047 --> 12:28.880
Gwen:
<i> And we're proud</i>
<i> to do our part.</i>

12:28.882 --> 12:33.651
It's just the folks on our
route seem to need extra care.

12:33.720 --> 12:35.987
If we could bring the training
that the black cross nurses

12:36.056 --> 12:37.655
Get in new york
to saint antoine-

12:37.724 --> 12:39.490
Eli:
<i> You are absolutely free</i>

12:39.559 --> 12:42.660
To pursue that training in
new york, sister massey.

12:42.729 --> 12:44.328
<i> Encouraged even.</i>

12:44.397 --> 12:46.664
<i> But we have to be</i>
<i> fiscally diligent.</i>

12:50.070 --> 12:52.870
The unia has its
own factories,

12:52.906 --> 12:53.805
Printing presses,

12:53.940 --> 12:55.406
Newspapers,

12:55.408 --> 12:57.008
Volunteers second to none.

12:58.912 --> 13:00.711
<i> But if we are ever</i>

13:00.747 --> 13:03.681
To restore the negro
to their rightful place,

13:03.750 --> 13:05.817
It's gonna take
every penny.

13:05.952 --> 13:07.885
Even the ones that
are hard to come by.

13:11.591 --> 13:13.691
<i> I look forward to</i>
<i> telling brother garvey</i>

13:13.760 --> 13:16.527
About your efforts at
the upcoming convention.

13:24.437 --> 13:25.636
Edwards:
<i> Now, as you can see,</i>

13:25.672 --> 13:28.439
<i> We have spared no expense</i>
<i> in our renovations.</i>

13:28.441 --> 13:30.441
Finest parisian fabrics,

13:30.443 --> 13:31.709
<i> Gold accents from egypt</i>

13:31.778 --> 13:32.877
And of course,

13:33.012 --> 13:35.013
Round the clock porter service
at the push of a button.

13:35.148 --> 13:36.347
(soft buzzing)

13:36.482 --> 13:43.721
(soft music)

13:43.790 --> 13:44.789
Yes sir.

13:44.791 --> 13:46.457
How can I be of service?

13:46.459 --> 13:51.796
(investors applaud)

13:51.798 --> 13:54.866
Edwards:
<i> When you invest in cc rail,</i>
<i> you can be sure you've made</i>

13:55.001 --> 13:56.868
A sound investment
in the future.

14:00.807 --> 14:01.872
Miller!

14:01.874 --> 14:03.141
(snaps fingers)

14:03.143 --> 14:04.942
Edwards:
<i> My investors are</i>
<i> melting in here.</i>

14:04.978 --> 14:06.410
<i> Fix it!</i>

14:06.479 --> 14:07.745
Miller:
<i> Right away, sir.</i>

14:08.548 --> 14:09.681
(henry softly reads aloud)

14:09.683 --> 14:11.149
Paper man:
<i> Local papers here!</i>
<i> Local papers!</i>

14:11.151 --> 14:12.750
(henry softly reads aloud)

14:12.819 --> 14:16.453
Paper man:
<i> Get your pictures, news,</i>
<i> read all about it!</i>

14:18.325 --> 14:20.391
Engineer's a
union job, henry.

14:20.526 --> 14:22.293
Maybe it's time we get
in the union then.

14:22.329 --> 14:25.496
Zeke:
<i> Oh, you think you're the first</i>
<i> person to think of that idea?</i>

14:25.498 --> 14:27.232
How you think we came up
with the welfare committee?

14:27.367 --> 14:29.433
So what,
we just accept it?

14:29.502 --> 14:31.102
Zeke:
<i> You better bury</i>
<i> that book, henry.</i>

14:34.674 --> 14:36.607
The president of
the damn railroad

14:36.676 --> 14:38.442
Is sweating through
his suit in there.

14:38.511 --> 14:40.111
Ice needs a reload, now!

14:40.180 --> 14:44.249
The ccr handbook's firm on
that being a six man job, sir.

14:44.384 --> 14:45.516
Maybe some of the men
from the kitchen

14:45.518 --> 14:46.817
They could lend a hand.

14:47.821 --> 14:50.188
Got all the hands
you're gonna get boy.

14:50.190 --> 14:51.488
Get it done.

14:54.060 --> 14:57.095
Announcer:
<i> Last call for the l train</i>
<i> leaving on platform 4.</i>

14:57.230 --> 15:00.798
<i> Last call for the l train</i>
<i> leaving on platform 4.</i>

15:00.867 --> 15:02.100
Junior say how
long he'd be?

15:02.235 --> 15:03.500
Does he ever?

15:03.536 --> 15:05.270
(winchester sucks his teeth)

15:05.405 --> 15:06.738
Come on now henry.

15:06.740 --> 15:08.839
Henry:
<i> Them union boys don't</i>
<i> have to take this shit.</i>

15:10.210 --> 15:11.276
Male passenger:
<i> Here, hang this up.</i>

15:11.411 --> 15:19.550
(indistinct chatter)

15:19.552 --> 15:20.484
Winchester:
<i> Come on henry!</i>

15:20.553 --> 15:22.353
Come here.

15:22.389 --> 15:23.687
Alright, come on.

15:26.893 --> 15:27.959
Hand it, boy.

15:28.094 --> 15:29.493
<i> Here, here.</i>
<i> All right.</i>

15:32.598 --> 15:34.365
Henry:
<i> All this complaining</i>
<i> "it's too hot",</i>

15:35.668 --> 15:37.068
How long you think before
they're gripin' it's too cold?

15:37.203 --> 15:38.236
Get it! Get it!

15:38.238 --> 15:40.037
(winchester laughs)

15:40.573 --> 15:41.673
(creaking)

15:41.808 --> 15:44.809
Zeke:
<i> Okay henry,</i>
<i> lets get this ice down!</i>

15:44.944 --> 15:46.177
<i> Keep it steady!</i>

15:47.047 --> 15:48.012
<i> Winn, you ready?</i>
-Uh huh.

15:49.215 --> 15:50.047
Zeke:
<i> Henry you got it steady?</i>

15:50.083 --> 15:51.548
Yeah.

15:52.419 --> 15:53.584
Alright, here we go!

15:53.586 --> 15:54.518
(grunting)

15:54.587 --> 15:56.053
Zeke:
<i> Keep it tight, win!</i>

15:57.123 --> 15:58.189
(grunting)

15:58.258 --> 15:59.523
Henry:
<i> I can't hold it!</i>

16:01.094 --> 16:02.327
Zeke:
<i> Henry, come on.</i>

16:03.329 --> 16:04.395
(shoes squeaking)

16:04.431 --> 16:06.264
(tense music)

16:06.266 --> 16:07.198
Henry!

16:07.267 --> 16:08.266
(henry cries out)

16:08.268 --> 16:15.206
(tense music)

16:15.275 --> 16:17.275
♪

16:17.277 --> 16:18.676
Winn go get some help!

16:18.811 --> 16:19.944
Go!

16:19.946 --> 16:26.951
(tense music)

16:26.953 --> 16:34.892
♪

17:00.453 --> 17:01.853
Henry.

17:03.456 --> 17:05.056
There just wasn't
enough hands.

17:07.193 --> 17:08.392
Junior:
<i> You should have waited.</i>

17:09.295 --> 17:10.761
Should've made him wait.

17:12.498 --> 17:13.597
F-for what?

17:13.633 --> 17:15.133
Them white workers
to get off their ass

17:15.135 --> 17:16.200
Or for dinger
to fire us all?

17:16.335 --> 17:18.202
Well fired is a whole lot
better than dead ain't it.

17:19.172 --> 17:20.071
So this is my fault?

17:20.140 --> 17:21.739
You got three
years to his one.

17:21.808 --> 17:22.807
Three fucking years!

17:22.809 --> 17:23.808
You know better!

17:23.877 --> 17:25.143
You should've stopped
him from going up there.

17:25.145 --> 17:27.945
Yeah and where the
hell were you, huh?

17:28.648 --> 17:30.148
<i> Hmm?</i>

17:30.150 --> 17:31.215
<i> Running off on one</i>
<i> of your schemes</i>

17:31.350 --> 17:32.550
Because junior massey
is too damn proud

17:32.685 --> 17:33.818
To put his hand
out for tips!

17:33.820 --> 17:36.754
Zeke, dinger wants to
see you on the train.

17:45.331 --> 17:52.236
(sombre music)

17:52.371 --> 18:02.380
♪

18:02.382 --> 18:12.389
♪

18:12.425 --> 18:22.333
♪

18:22.402 --> 18:28.672
♪

18:28.708 --> 18:30.875
(man laughs)

18:30.877 --> 18:44.622
(indistinct chatter)

18:44.757 --> 18:46.490
Excuse me
just a moment.

18:48.161 --> 18:50.161
Mr. Miller said you
wanted to see me, sir?

18:50.230 --> 18:51.295
William edwards.

18:51.430 --> 18:53.164
I understand you're the
top man on my train.

18:53.233 --> 18:55.699
Well I can't rightly say
where I fall on the scale,

18:55.735 --> 18:59.170
But I've been known to
keep a cool head sir.

18:59.305 --> 19:01.305
They have to bring
the body this way

19:01.440 --> 19:03.040
And we can't
afford any upset.

19:04.043 --> 19:06.043
Just keep them away
from the windows.

19:06.079 --> 19:07.511
Give them whatever they
need to stay happy.

19:08.915 --> 19:11.582
I'll make sure that
they're comfortable, sir.

19:11.584 --> 19:13.884
And I want liquor flowing
like a river in here.

19:14.787 --> 19:16.020
If they can forget
their own names,

19:16.089 --> 19:17.387
No chance they'll
remember all this.

19:17.423 --> 19:19.991
Well I would reconsider
the river, sir.

19:21.761 --> 19:25.529
Mr. Lewis and mr. Brenner
were guests some time ago.

19:26.933 --> 19:31.735
Both devout mormons if I recall
from our last conversation.

19:31.771 --> 19:35.206
Now as shrewd an investment
as this railway is,

19:35.275 --> 19:37.208
They'd count the liquor as
a strike against you, sir.

19:40.113 --> 19:42.079
Miller said you had a
mind like a steel trap.

19:43.283 --> 19:45.082
A blessing and a
curse I'm afraid.

19:46.619 --> 19:50.021
Well alright,
dry the river.

19:53.826 --> 20:00.698
(soft blues music)

20:00.833 --> 20:10.841
♪

20:10.843 --> 20:19.317
♪

20:19.319 --> 20:26.257
(tense dramatic music)

20:26.326 --> 20:39.737
♪

20:39.872 --> 20:41.272
(muffled gunshot)

20:41.341 --> 20:49.146
(tense dramatic music)

21:01.694 --> 21:02.760
I, um-

21:02.895 --> 21:05.763
I know you were close
to the boy, so, uh,

21:05.898 --> 21:07.431
<i> Make sure this</i>
<i> gets to his people.</i>

21:14.540 --> 21:19.310
<i> Porters, items missing</i>
<i> from the common area:</i>

21:19.445 --> 21:21.478
<i> Three bars soap,</i>
<i> pack of chesterfields,</i>

21:21.547 --> 21:24.481
<i> And a jar of pickled</i>
<i> onions from the lounge car.</i>

21:24.550 --> 21:26.717
Glenford:
<i> Mr. Miller, you</i>
<i> know very well</i>

21:26.719 --> 21:28.319
That passengers take those
things all the time.

21:28.454 --> 21:30.988
Right. To be split
equally amongst you then.

21:31.057 --> 21:33.457
<i> And a demerit for mr. Brown</i>
<i> for poor conduct.</i>

21:33.592 --> 21:36.360
Mr. Massey, two blankets
missing from your car.

21:36.396 --> 21:37.861
<i> Three-fifty apiece</i>
<i> makes seven,</i>

21:37.897 --> 21:39.863
<i> To be deducted from</i>
<i> your paycheque.</i>

21:48.074 --> 21:49.873
Why didn't you make
the white boys help?

21:53.413 --> 21:55.179
<i> Three men on a job for six,</i>
<i> what'd you think would happen?</i>

21:55.248 --> 21:56.147
Miller:
<i> Watch yourself,</i>
<i> mr. Massey.</i>

21:56.282 --> 21:57.315
Right, because you
don't give a shit.

21:57.450 --> 21:58.616
Miller:
<i> Okay, two demerits.</i>

21:58.751 --> 22:00.017
Boss had to stay cool and the
train had to leave on time-

22:00.086 --> 22:01.252
Three demerits!

22:01.387 --> 22:02.853
So to hell with the nigger
had to die to make it happen!

22:02.922 --> 22:06.190
There has to be some
consideration for grief.

22:06.259 --> 22:10.894
(tense dramatic music)

22:10.930 --> 22:13.897
Sir, you have
passengers of prominence

22:13.933 --> 22:16.367
That insist on
junior alone.

22:16.502 --> 22:19.170
That kind of disappointment can
be quite costly to the company.

22:20.940 --> 22:22.906
One demerit left,
mr. Massey.

22:24.043 --> 22:26.110
Seems that you have some
careful treading to do.

22:26.112 --> 22:33.050
(tense dramatic music)

22:33.119 --> 22:43.093
♪

22:43.162 --> 22:53.137
♪

22:53.206 --> 23:03.146
♪

23:03.182 --> 23:13.123
♪

23:32.845 --> 23:34.311
Lucy:
<i> C'mon.</i>

23:35.548 --> 23:36.747
Dance with me.

23:44.723 --> 23:49.593
(metal clatters)

24:02.708 --> 24:04.275
Marlene:
<i> What's going on?</i>

24:04.410 --> 24:05.876
Henry's dead

24:05.878 --> 24:08.678
And the railroad sent his
family a bill for the uniform.

24:10.082 --> 24:11.482
<i> Fucking uniform!</i>

24:11.551 --> 24:16.454
<i> ♪ there ain't</i>
<i> nothin' I can do,</i>

24:17.289 --> 24:21.158
<i> ♪ or nothin' I can say</i>

24:22.628 --> 24:33.537
♪ that folks don't
criticize me

24:33.573 --> 24:43.514
<i> ♪ but I'm going to do</i>
<i> just as I want to anyway</i>

24:44.750 --> 24:54.658
♪ and don't care if
they all despise me

24:56.929 --> 25:02.266
♪ if I should
take a notion

25:02.268 --> 25:07.070
<i> ♪ to jump into the ocean,</i>

25:07.106 --> 25:08.672
♪<i> t'aint nobody's</i>
<i> bizness if I doooo</i> ♪

25:08.674 --> 25:09.906
Bobby, it's me.

25:11.477 --> 25:13.243
Let's get that
grown-up money.

25:21.954 --> 25:24.754
(bottles clatter)

25:27.627 --> 25:28.892
Welcome junior.

25:31.731 --> 25:33.597
I need fifty bottles
of whiskey popsy.

25:36.302 --> 25:37.701
Just like that, eh?

25:39.305 --> 25:40.704
Just like that.

25:42.141 --> 25:43.574
Who's your buyer?

25:44.910 --> 25:47.110
Nobody in competition with you,
so no worries there, eh.

25:47.146 --> 25:48.445
(junior chuckles)

25:48.481 --> 25:50.381
Them kind of numbers
people are gonna notice.

25:52.151 --> 25:54.618
Sometimes it's a dangerous
thing to be seen.

25:58.157 --> 25:59.590
I'm a porter, popsy.

26:00.660 --> 26:02.792
The most invisible
man on the earth.

26:02.828 --> 26:05.795
(popsy laughs)

26:07.533 --> 26:09.066
You forgot junior,

26:09.201 --> 26:10.734
That I'm not the
type of negro

26:10.869 --> 26:12.736
That constables
care to tolerate.

26:13.872 --> 26:15.839
<i> Comes out I'm</i>
<i> supplying a smuggler,</i>

26:15.841 --> 26:18.075
I will go broke paying
to keep this place open.

26:20.846 --> 26:22.145
I won't get caught.

26:22.181 --> 26:23.980
Everybody says
that 'til they do.

26:25.785 --> 26:26.983
I'm not everybody.

26:31.390 --> 26:32.822
Heard about henry.

26:35.695 --> 26:36.960
<i> How you doing?</i>

26:40.032 --> 26:41.831
Can you supply
me or not?

26:51.377 --> 26:52.976
Yeah, I'll get
your liquor.

26:54.913 --> 26:56.447
But you promise
me something.

26:58.917 --> 27:00.050
This starts to smell funny,
you get out,

27:00.052 --> 27:01.385
You hear me?

27:01.387 --> 27:03.320
This whole world that
you're trying to get into,

27:03.455 --> 27:04.988
That is the one formula.

27:06.925 --> 27:09.993
Knowing when to be a
bull-headed negro motherfucker.

27:11.731 --> 27:12.996
<i> And when not to be.</i>

27:17.236 --> 27:20.671
Well, I'll certainly try.

27:25.110 --> 27:26.477
Put in ice!

27:30.082 --> 27:32.849
(sombre music)

27:32.918 --> 27:36.086
(kids laughing)

27:36.088 --> 27:37.387
Child:
<i> Oh no! Run!</i>

27:37.423 --> 27:39.055
(kids laughing)

27:39.091 --> 27:42.760
(indistinct chatter)

27:42.762 --> 27:44.227
Pastor haynes:
<i> Got some, uh,</i>
<i> scotch pepper.</i>

27:44.263 --> 27:45.562
Eli:
<i> Oh you know I love me</i>
<i> some scotch pepper</i>

27:45.598 --> 27:48.766
I got some carrots,
got some cabbage.

27:48.768 --> 27:50.033
Eli:
<i> Mighty impressive.</i>

27:50.102 --> 27:51.168
I've got some aloe.

27:51.303 --> 27:53.036
Eli:
<i> Aloe, that's very...</i>

27:56.108 --> 27:58.408
Pastor haynes:
<i> Sister marlene,</i>
<i> sister gwen!</i>

27:59.945 --> 28:02.045
Thank you so much for
answering the call.

28:03.315 --> 28:05.516
Not everyone's equipped
for this sort of thing.

28:15.795 --> 28:16.860
Oh.

28:20.466 --> 28:21.865
Hey there henry.

28:29.308 --> 28:32.275
The railroad billed his family
for the uniform he died in.

28:33.646 --> 28:36.814
So, it looks like
the association

28:36.816 --> 28:40.417
Is gonna have to step up and
cover his funeral costs

28:40.486 --> 28:41.752
<i> Since we're the only</i>
<i> family he's got.</i>

28:41.821 --> 28:45.889
Ah, would that we could,
sister massey.

28:46.024 --> 28:49.626
But our resources are
stretched thin as it is.

28:49.662 --> 28:51.161
So, nothing.

28:51.163 --> 28:53.831
That's what you're
offering this boy.

28:53.833 --> 28:59.903
And I would say that the
loan of our two finest nurses

29:00.038 --> 29:01.905
<i> Is a generous</i>
<i> offering indeed.</i>

29:06.879 --> 29:10.647
Well, there's his true
colours on display.

29:10.683 --> 29:12.148
That's all right, gwen.

29:13.185 --> 29:14.785
That man ain't seen
a shade of mine yet.

29:17.857 --> 29:19.122
(gwen sighs)

29:28.534 --> 29:29.800
(sombre music)

29:29.869 --> 29:31.802
Gwen:
<i> Grant him eternal rest.</i>

29:33.405 --> 29:35.773
The light perpetual,
shine upon him.

29:37.710 --> 29:40.677
<i> May his soul and the</i>
<i> souls of all the departed</i>

29:40.713 --> 29:41.812
Rest in peace, amen.

29:41.881 --> 29:46.850
(solemn music)

29:46.986 --> 29:49.620
<i> ♪ the funeral started</i>

29:49.755 --> 29:54.892
<i> ♪ 'fore they came down</i>

29:54.894 --> 29:58.462
<i> ♪ the funeral started</i>

29:58.597 --> 30:02.833
<i> ♪ 'fore they came down ♪</i>

30:02.902 --> 30:06.904
(indistinct chatter)

30:06.906 --> 30:11.374
<i> ♪ before they came down</i>

30:11.410 --> 30:15.245
<i> ♪ long time back, lord</i>

30:15.247 --> 30:19.983
<i> ♪ long time back ♪</i>

30:20.118 --> 30:21.752
(solemn music)

30:21.754 --> 30:22.986
(door knocks)

30:25.624 --> 30:26.590
<i> Henry's things.</i>

30:26.592 --> 30:28.659
Didn't want the landlady
throwing them out.

30:29.261 --> 30:36.266
(solemn music)

30:36.268 --> 30:46.276
♪

30:46.312 --> 30:56.353
♪

30:56.355 --> 31:06.330
♪

31:06.332 --> 31:16.373
♪

31:16.508 --> 31:26.316
♪

31:26.352 --> 31:39.930
♪

31:39.932 --> 31:46.770
(indistinct chatter)
(soft piano music)

31:46.839 --> 31:56.479
♪

31:56.515 --> 32:02.485
(typewriter clicking)

32:11.229 --> 32:12.429
Excuse me.

32:17.235 --> 32:18.501
Excuse me, ma'am?

32:20.539 --> 32:22.105
Dianne, see about getting
me some lunch will you?

32:22.240 --> 32:23.539
Ah, mr. Edwards.

32:24.376 --> 32:25.709
<i> Ah, zeke garrett.</i>

32:25.844 --> 32:28.045
I met you on your
train to chicago.

32:28.047 --> 32:30.680
I was wondering if I could
have a moment of your time sir?

32:31.550 --> 32:33.016
The steel trap.

32:44.396 --> 32:45.862
Have a seat mr garrett.

32:58.577 --> 33:01.544
Mr. Edwards, this is
a growing company,

33:01.580 --> 33:04.081
And on all accounts
a very profitable one.

33:04.083 --> 33:06.883
And I believe we porters
play no small part in that.

33:08.587 --> 33:12.489
But good men
shouldn't have to die

33:12.624 --> 33:13.890
To make this
company great.

33:16.028 --> 33:17.727
There needs to be a
change here, sir.

33:18.764 --> 33:20.163
Well.

33:21.433 --> 33:24.901
Mr. Garrett, I must say
your timing is fortuitous.

33:27.272 --> 33:30.239
<i> Renovation plans for that line</i>
<i> will make side-loading doors</i>

33:30.275 --> 33:32.843
The standard for
cooling cars.

33:32.978 --> 33:34.945
<i> No more risky climbs.</i>

33:34.947 --> 33:35.846
<i> Your young porter-</i>

33:35.981 --> 33:37.213
Henry.

33:38.450 --> 33:39.916
His name was henry.

33:41.253 --> 33:44.587
Henry's untimely passing has
only spurred on our efforts.

33:45.557 --> 33:46.589
I've instructed the
welfare committee

33:46.625 --> 33:48.257
To let your fellow
porters know,

33:48.293 --> 33:49.860
Change is on the way.

33:51.830 --> 33:53.763
That's just one
small part, sir.

33:55.134 --> 33:58.201
The porters have chipped
in what they could,

33:58.336 --> 34:00.537
But there's still costs
outstanding, his uniform-

34:00.672 --> 34:02.605
Where were you
recruited from garrett?

34:06.145 --> 34:07.878
Here.

34:08.013 --> 34:09.278
Right after the war, sir.

34:10.149 --> 34:11.614
No.

34:12.951 --> 34:16.619
No, I remember that bunch,
handpicked most of them myself.

34:16.655 --> 34:19.890
I-I was in wales when that
first group started here.

34:21.026 --> 34:22.425
So you were there
for the riots?

34:23.829 --> 34:25.228
No.

34:25.363 --> 34:27.564
I was halfway home by then,

34:27.699 --> 34:29.632
Leg injury.

34:29.668 --> 34:32.836
(soft music)

34:32.838 --> 34:34.804
That was some
nasty business.

34:36.175 --> 34:38.441
Good to know you weren't
one of the agitators.

34:42.848 --> 34:44.447
But to your primary
concern mr. Garrett,

34:44.516 --> 34:45.982
Change takes time.

34:47.385 --> 34:49.853
If that's not something
you're willing to wait for,

34:49.855 --> 34:51.121
Feel free to turn
in your uniform

34:51.190 --> 34:53.656
To any of the men standing
in line to wear it.

34:57.729 --> 35:01.464
Thank you for your
time mr. Edwards.

35:01.533 --> 35:03.332
I know it's a
valuable commodity.

35:11.543 --> 35:12.809
Dianne.

35:14.246 --> 35:15.545
Sir.

35:15.547 --> 35:17.280
Go through the
porter contracts,

35:18.884 --> 35:21.151
See if you can find one
for ezekiel garrett.

35:32.230 --> 35:42.205
♪

35:42.241 --> 35:52.182
♪

35:52.317 --> 35:58.187
♪

35:58.223 --> 35:59.456
Beer please.

36:00.258 --> 36:01.458
Beer?

36:01.593 --> 36:04.394
Thought you tycoon types
had fancier taste.

36:04.396 --> 36:05.662
Not really.

36:05.731 --> 36:07.997
Money's just easy to
spend when it's not yours.

36:14.506 --> 36:17.373
Don't think this tip will turn
into an hourly wage later.

36:19.277 --> 36:21.010
I don't want that
kind of girl.

36:22.280 --> 36:24.046
I want to know what
kind of girl you are.

36:27.285 --> 36:28.485
Can I see you later?

36:31.423 --> 36:38.461
(upbeat jazz music)

36:38.463 --> 36:48.404
♪

36:48.473 --> 36:54.377
♪

36:59.785 --> 37:02.084
(corrine sobs)

37:15.333 --> 37:17.200
I'm so sorry about henry.

37:18.670 --> 37:20.269
Why do people keep
saying that to me?

37:20.305 --> 37:22.071
We weren't married
or nothing.

37:30.148 --> 37:31.548
Corrine.

37:33.151 --> 37:35.951
If you need some time off I'm
sure popsy'd give it to you.

37:37.823 --> 37:41.090
And I could cover your part as
long as you need me to just-

37:41.159 --> 37:42.625
<i> Just say the word.</i>

37:59.511 --> 38:01.310
(slaps)
(lucy gasps)

38:01.346 --> 38:03.513
I know who you
are lucy-mae.

38:03.515 --> 38:04.447
Corinne, I never
meant it as a-

38:04.516 --> 38:05.782
You think I'm out front

38:05.851 --> 38:07.817
Just because I'm cream
and you're coffee.

38:09.387 --> 38:11.788
I'm better lucy.

38:11.923 --> 38:13.423
You wanna get off
the back row,

38:13.558 --> 38:16.325
Try a little talent.

38:16.361 --> 38:19.128
But leave henry out of it!

38:33.144 --> 38:43.986
(moaning)

38:52.397 --> 38:54.864
(both laugh)

39:14.452 --> 39:16.385
You all alone in this
great big house?

39:17.455 --> 39:18.721
Feels that way.

39:19.691 --> 39:20.857
Father has me in this
whole other wing

39:20.926 --> 39:22.558
So he doesn't have
to look at my face.

39:26.598 --> 39:28.097
<i> Uh uh.</i>

39:28.100 --> 39:31.000
This voice is my
ticket to new york.

39:31.136 --> 39:33.269
I'm not about to
burn it with smoke.

39:33.271 --> 39:35.237
Franklin:
<i> If new york is the goal,</i>

39:36.608 --> 39:37.874
What are you doing here?

39:38.944 --> 39:40.910
Lucy:
<i> Every dream has a price.</i>

39:40.946 --> 39:42.545
Stardust is fine,

39:42.614 --> 39:45.080
But b-squad
doesn't get noticed.

39:45.117 --> 39:46.749
I could help with that.

39:51.289 --> 39:53.022
I make my own way.

39:53.158 --> 39:54.590
Franklin:
<i> I'm the same.</i>

39:55.927 --> 39:58.427
Least I would be if my father
would just give me a chance.

40:11.476 --> 40:12.442
(door knocks)

40:12.511 --> 40:14.276
Servant:
<i>Master edward,</i>
<i>dinner is served.</i>

40:15.313 --> 40:22.251
(delicate classical music)

40:22.320 --> 40:32.362
♪

40:32.364 --> 40:40.003
♪

40:40.005 --> 40:41.737
You don't need to send
the help to fetch me,

40:41.739 --> 40:42.672
I know what
time dinner is.

40:42.807 --> 40:44.507
Well then perhaps you
could show some respect

40:44.509 --> 40:45.808
And act on it.

40:45.844 --> 40:47.510
Apologies, father.

40:47.512 --> 40:49.645
I will certainly
aim to improve.

40:51.183 --> 40:52.448
Clerk:
(in french)<i> no I can't.</i>

40:52.517 --> 40:54.149
Lance:
<i> What do you mean you</i>
<i> can't give me credit?</i>

40:54.853 --> 40:56.285
<i> I always pay my bill.</i>

40:56.354 --> 40:59.355
Clerk:
<i> Sorry, I can't. Okay?</i>

40:59.357 --> 41:00.623
I got him.

41:03.695 --> 41:05.160
Clerk:
<i> Oh, merci.</i>

41:05.831 --> 41:07.496
(cash register dings)

41:17.775 --> 41:19.709
I can pay you
back next week.

41:19.711 --> 41:21.444
I got myself a little part-time
job until the railroad-

41:21.579 --> 41:22.845
Don't worry
about the money.

41:23.982 --> 41:25.715
But there's something
else you can do for me.

41:25.717 --> 41:30.453
(suspenseful music)

41:30.588 --> 41:33.355
Junior:
<i> That part-time job you work</i>
<i> is at the ice factory, right?</i>

41:34.059 --> 41:35.524
Lance:
<i> Yeah.</i>

41:37.562 --> 41:39.662
Junior:
<i> How much a special delivery</i>
<i> run for these days?</i>

41:42.567 --> 41:44.033
Lance:
<i> Wha the fuck you up to?</i>

41:45.237 --> 41:51.540
(dramatic suspenseful music)

41:51.576 --> 41:54.209
Train announcer:
<i> All passengers continuing</i>
<i> on to the united states,</i>

41:54.246 --> 41:55.812
<i> Have your passports ready.</i>

41:55.947 --> 42:04.087
(dramatic suspenseful music)

42:04.089 --> 42:05.488
Is there a problem george?

42:08.093 --> 42:15.665
(dramatic suspenseful music)

42:15.800 --> 42:19.902
(train whistle roars)

42:19.938 --> 42:26.742
(dramatic suspenseful music)

42:27.645 --> 42:28.577
The man you trust
with your life

42:28.613 --> 42:30.046
Doesn't know how
to tell time, huh?

42:30.115 --> 42:36.519
(rhythmic trumpet music)

42:36.654 --> 42:38.054
(bobby laughs)

42:38.123 --> 42:39.421
I told you!

42:40.792 --> 42:48.531
(rhythmic trumpet music)

42:48.666 --> 42:50.766
Junior, this here
chuck monnastes.

42:52.637 --> 42:55.204
In the cooling system, huh?

42:55.340 --> 42:56.539
That's real innovative.

42:56.674 --> 42:57.740
You think of
that yourself?

42:57.809 --> 42:58.875
Bobby:
<i> Junior's no dummy.</i>

42:59.010 --> 43:00.776
<i> He'll think you out</i>
<i> from under your hat.</i>

43:01.913 --> 43:03.445
Alright, I'll give you
two dollars a bottle.

43:06.318 --> 43:07.616
We agreed on four.

43:08.486 --> 43:09.952
Now we disagree.

43:10.822 --> 43:12.088
Come on, chuck.
Four's fair now.

43:12.157 --> 43:13.656
Monnastes:
<i> Hey bobby?</i>

43:13.658 --> 43:14.857
Shut up.

43:14.859 --> 43:17.160
(tense music swells)

43:17.162 --> 43:18.094
If I drive away,

43:18.163 --> 43:19.896
What are you gonna do?

43:20.031 --> 43:20.897
You can't sit out
here with it,

43:21.032 --> 43:22.231
You'll be in jail
by hour's end.

43:22.367 --> 43:26.069
So unless you wanna freeze it
back up and smuggle it home,

43:26.204 --> 43:27.503
<i> Two seems fair.</i>

43:27.505 --> 43:33.976
(tense music)

43:34.012 --> 43:35.912
♪

43:36.047 --> 43:37.914
You can get this one
right here for two.

43:39.517 --> 43:40.950
(bottle shatters)

43:42.187 --> 43:43.652
But these cost four.

43:43.688 --> 43:45.121
There it is.

43:45.190 --> 43:47.156
There's that simian
brain taking over.

43:49.527 --> 43:50.626
(bottle shatters)

43:50.662 --> 43:53.863
Jeez-us. Chuck, we supposed
to make a delivery.

43:53.865 --> 43:54.930
<i> Can we just</i>
<i> get this done?</i>

43:54.932 --> 43:55.965
(bottle shatters)
oh.

43:56.034 --> 43:57.199
Alright, fine, fine.

43:57.235 --> 43:58.467
Two-fifty, alright?
Stop making an ass of yourself.

43:58.536 --> 43:59.602
Two-fifty, bobby.

43:59.737 --> 44:01.670
This motherfucker wants
to give me two-fifty!

44:01.706 --> 44:04.006
Monnastes:
<i> Listen crackerjack,</i>
<i> there's some real basic math</i>

44:04.042 --> 44:05.108
You're failing to
grasp here, alright?

44:05.243 --> 44:06.341
Bobby.

44:06.378 --> 44:08.644
Fine, alright!

44:10.048 --> 44:11.513
<i> Fine, four dollars.</i>

44:11.549 --> 44:14.483
Four apiece for the ones that
are left you fucking lunatic.

44:20.058 --> 44:22.024
You're a real cocky coon,
aren'tcha?

44:23.928 --> 44:26.862
<i> Well, I hope it was worth it.</i>

44:28.433 --> 44:31.968
It was worth every penny,
crackerjack.

44:33.104 --> 44:34.870
Bobby take care
of your man here.

44:40.945 --> 44:47.850
(solemn organ music)

44:47.985 --> 44:51.053
♪

44:51.122 --> 44:54.524
For all the
weight and worry

44:54.659 --> 44:57.059
We place on this
thing called life

44:59.464 --> 45:00.929
It's simply a chapter,

45:03.134 --> 45:04.767
A moment,

45:05.870 --> 45:07.436
A vapour,

45:09.808 --> 45:12.074
<i> Visible only for</i>
<i> a sliver of time.</i>

45:13.812 --> 45:15.745
<i> And while we may sorrow,</i>

45:17.315 --> 45:18.914
<i> We hold no fear of death,</i>

45:20.485 --> 45:23.886
For we know death has
already been defeated.

45:24.021 --> 45:26.589
(indistinct chatter)

45:26.658 --> 45:29.759
Pastor haynes:
<i> What hurts us,</i>
<i> can heal us.</i>

45:30.995 --> 45:33.496
<i> But the pain</i>
<i> that divides us,</i>

45:33.498 --> 45:35.431
<i> Need not defeat us.</i>

45:35.500 --> 45:36.965
Parishioner:
<i> Yes lord, praise the lord!</i>

45:37.001 --> 45:38.300
Parishioner 2:
<i> Lord knows.</i>

45:38.336 --> 45:39.769
Parishioner 3:
<i> Amen.</i>

45:39.838 --> 45:41.103
Pallbearers.

46:13.872 --> 46:21.143
(sombre piano music)

46:21.212 --> 46:31.154
♪

46:31.289 --> 46:45.367
♪

46:45.403 --> 46:47.202
Pastor haynes:
<i> We are broken sometimes.</i>

46:51.576 --> 46:53.576
<i> We are struggling sometimes.</i>

46:53.578 --> 47:00.583
(sombre piano music)

47:00.585 --> 47:04.987
♪

47:05.122 --> 47:08.390
Pastor haynes:
<i> Sometimes we are</i>
<i> angry at the god</i>

47:08.426 --> 47:11.894
<i> We feel has left</i>
<i> us to languish.</i>

47:12.030 --> 47:14.330
<i> But we are family,</i>

47:18.603 --> 47:20.002
<i> And what we are,</i>

47:23.107 --> 47:24.874
<i> What we've always been</i>

47:27.612 --> 47:28.911
<i> Is hope.</i>

47:30.147 --> 47:37.787
(melancholic music)

47:37.789 --> 47:39.689
Pastor haynes:
<i> We are here,</i>

47:45.463 --> 47:48.430
<i> And we are hope.</i>

47:51.970 --> 47:58.975
(melancholic music)

47:58.977 --> 48:03.779
♪

48:13.658 --> 48:15.057
To henry.

48:17.328 --> 48:18.728
Welcome home brother.

48:30.508 --> 48:32.274
I spoke to the big boss.

48:35.013 --> 48:36.746
I think he knows
about kinmel.

48:39.684 --> 48:41.951
Not everything,
but, but not nothin'.

48:46.691 --> 48:48.657
Well whatever he
thinks he knows,

48:49.827 --> 48:51.660
We don't give him a reason
to look any further.

48:53.197 --> 48:54.496
<i> You got it?</i>

48:56.534 --> 48:57.767
Alright.

49:03.041 --> 49:05.041
(indistinct chatter)

49:05.043 --> 49:08.044
(soft dramatic music)

49:08.046 --> 49:09.779
Lance you out here?

49:09.914 --> 49:16.852
(soft dramatic music)

49:16.888 --> 49:18.120
♪

49:18.255 --> 49:19.488
<i> Lets have a warm welcome</i>

49:19.557 --> 49:21.724
<i> For our comrade</i>
<i> mr. A. Philip randolph.</i>

49:21.726 --> 49:24.126
(audience clapping)

49:25.463 --> 49:29.398
The history of the labour
movement in north america proves

49:29.400 --> 49:33.135
The employing class
recognizes no race lines.

49:33.270 --> 49:34.803
(audience affirmations)

49:34.872 --> 49:37.873
Randolph:
<i> They will exploit a white</i>
<i> man as readily as a black man.</i>

49:37.909 --> 49:40.977
<i> They will exploit women</i>
<i> as readily as men.</i>

49:41.112 --> 49:44.546
Unions are not based
upon race lines,

49:44.582 --> 49:48.550
But upon class lines.

49:48.586 --> 49:51.087
<i> In organization</i>
<i> there is strength.</i>

49:51.089 --> 49:54.056
(audience applauds)

50:00.198 --> 50:03.065
Look, I got no say on where
and how you live your life

50:04.268 --> 50:06.568
<i> But let's be clear bobby,</i>

50:06.604 --> 50:10.506
Outside of chicago you and
I ain't fuckin' familiar.

50:10.641 --> 50:12.174
You understand me?

50:14.645 --> 50:16.178
Randolph:
<i> Do not be deceived,</i>

50:17.281 --> 50:20.182
I am not the enemy here.

50:22.120 --> 50:24.186
And yet I have been called

50:24.321 --> 50:26.588
"the most dangerous
negro in america".

50:26.624 --> 50:29.424
(audience laughs)

50:32.130 --> 50:35.230
Randolph:
<i> Unity is our ammunition!</i>

50:35.299 --> 50:37.066
(audience applauds)

50:37.201 --> 50:38.934
I'm sorry junior.

50:39.837 --> 50:42.038
(junior grunts)

50:42.173 --> 50:43.205
Bobby!

50:43.207 --> 50:45.607
(grunting)

50:45.643 --> 50:49.478
(pummeling)

50:49.480 --> 50:50.412
Officer:
<i> Hands up, bolsheviks!</i>

50:50.481 --> 50:52.081
(rifle cocks)
(audience gasps)

50:52.150 --> 50:57.153
(crowd shouting)
(dramatic music)

50:57.155 --> 50:58.420
(grunting)
(pummeling)

50:58.555 --> 50:59.655
(board cracking)

50:59.657 --> 51:06.628
(dramatic suspenseful music)

51:06.664 --> 51:11.433
♪
